00:05:39.139 --> 00:05:50.709
The first thing is a discount
bond.

00:05:50.709 --> 00:06:01.781
It's the most simple--or often
called a bill--a discount bond

00:06:01.781 --> 00:06:08.750
does not pay interest;
it's sold at a discount.

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:16.310
You have the principle,
which is the amount owed,

00:06:16.310 --> 00:06:24.347
which is, let's say it's $100,
that will be paid to you at

00:06:24.347 --> 00:06:30.120
some date in the future,
specified in the contract.

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:35.290
And nothing,
you would just get $100.

00:06:35.290 --> 00:06:39.435
Effectively,
you get interest from this

00:06:39.435 --> 00:06:45.980
because it's sold at a discount,
so the price that you pay is

00:06:45.980 --> 00:06:50.780
equal to one hundred minus the
discount.

00:06:55.949 --> 00:06:59.949
You wouldn't buy this bond at
par because--at par,

00:06:59.949 --> 00:07:04.928
meaning at $100--because then
you wouldn't get any interest on

00:07:04.928 --> 00:07:09.965
it.
So you buy it at a discount and

00:07:09.965 --> 00:07:18.896
the return you get is of course
a hundred minus--the return you

00:07:18.896 --> 00:07:24.720
get is the discount.
The U.S.

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:28.834
Government is a big issuer of
discount bonds and they're

00:07:28.834 --> 00:07:34.714
called Treasury bills.
I have them up on the screen

00:07:34.714 --> 00:07:37.759
here.
This is from a U.S.

00:07:37.759 --> 00:07:43.816
Government website called
treasurydirect.gov and you can

00:07:43.816 --> 00:07:47.670
get on and access it at any
time.

00:07:47.670 --> 00:07:53.044
It is showing--since the U.S.
Government issues these bonds,

00:07:53.044 --> 00:07:56.139
it's showing its data on these
bonds.

00:07:56.139 --> 00:08:03.346
The bonds are auctioned off on
