00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:43.165
Treasury bills--maybe you have
to realize there's a distinction

00:08:43.165 --> 00:08:46.110
between savings bonds and
Treasury bills.

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:49.894
Treasury bills are for serious
investors and so they don't come

00:08:49.894 --> 00:08:52.279
in small denominations.
The U.S.

00:08:52.279 --> 00:08:58.669
Government also issues small
denomination debt to individuals

00:08:58.669 --> 00:09:04.526
to help them called savings
bonds, but we aren't talking

00:09:04.526 --> 00:09:08.938
about those.
At the February 14^(th)

00:09:08.938 --> 00:09:15.178
auction, Treasury bills
were--sixty-day treasury bills

00:09:15.178 --> 00:09:20.360
were sold and the auction price
is given.

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:24.230
Well, here's the price of the
bill.

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:28.769
The issue date was today,
February 15^(th),

00:09:28.769 --> 00:09:35.362
and they mature in what should
be exactly sixty days--on April

00:09:35.362 --> 00:09:36.660
15^(th).

00:09:42.879 --> 00:09:47.009
If you want to buy one you
would pay this price.

00:09:47.009 --> 00:09:49.476
This number,
CUSIP number,

00:09:49.476 --> 00:09:53.720
is a number that identifies any
security.

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:56.881
It's like you have a social
security number or other ID

00:09:56.881 --> 00:10:00.570
number, which positively--there
might be another person with the

00:10:00.570 --> 00:10:03.553
same name as you,
God forbid, but you at least

00:10:03.553 --> 00:10:06.435
have your own number,
which is guaranteed to be

00:10:06.435 --> 00:10:09.714
unique to you.
So every security has an

00:10:09.714 --> 00:10:13.220
identical CUSIP,
which identifies it.

00:10:13.220 --> 00:10:21.280
I want to start by explaining
the numbers here.

00:10:26.639 --> 00:10:29.520
How did they get--how do these
numbers interrelate?

00:10:34.909 --> 00:10:40.116
Well, the discount rate is sort
of the--you notice there are two

00:10:40.116 --> 00:10:44.826
different interest rates here
and you might be confused by

00:10:44.826 --> 00:10:48.360
them.
The discount rate that is shown

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:53.850
is the number that you plug into
a formula to get the price.

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:59.884
What really matters to you as
an investor is how much you have

00:10:59.884 --> 00:11:03.940
to pay today to get $100 in
sixty days.

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:09.450
So, how do we get the price
from the discount rate?

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:16.587
Well, there's a formula that's
been used by bond traders for

00:11:16.587 --> 00:11:23.120
hundreds of years and it's a
traditional expression,

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:27.759
which goes from the discount
rate to the price.

00:11:27.759 --> 00:11:33.830
In this case,
price is $99.58 and what does

00:11:33.830 --> 00:11:41.681
that equal?
It equals 2.51--that's the

00:11:41.681 --> 00:11:55.690
discount rate that you see up
there--well, (2.510 x 60)/360.

00:11:55.690 --> 00:12:01.623
As you know,
the maturity is 60-days and,

00:12:01.623 --> 00:12:07.705
as you know,
there are about 360 days in a

00:12:07.705 --> 00:12:10.713
year.
By tradition,

00:12:10.713 --> 00:12:17.019
they divide by 360,
not 365, and so you understand

00:12:17.019 --> 00:12:23.970
that dealers of Treasury bills
tend to "discounts."

00:12:23.970 --> 00:12:27.840
It's like a language,
a language of finance.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:34.821
So what everybody knows is that
the discount is converted into a

00:12:34.821 --> 00:12:40.259
price according to this formula.
You might ask,

00:12:40.259 --> 00:12:44.670
well is this an approximate
formula?

00:12:44.670 --> 00:12:47.428
No, it's an exact formula.
Then you say,

00:12:47.428 --> 00:12:52.368
well why didn't they divide by
365, because I know there are

00:12:52.368 --> 00:12:56.667
365 days in a year?
The answer is--this goes way

00:12:56.667 --> 00:13:02.107
back--it's an old tradition and
they used to have to do this by

00:13:02.107 --> 00:13:05.055
hand.
They had to divide by hand and

00:13:05.055 --> 00:13:08.874
so they didn't like the number
365, so they thought,

00:13:08.874 --> 00:13:12.570
let's just round it to 360.
As long as everybody knows

00:13:12.570 --> 00:13:15.527
that's what we're doing,
what difference does it make,

00:13:15.527 --> 00:13:18.304
right?
That's what you're supposed to

00:13:18.304 --> 00:13:20.402
know.
If your dealer quotes you a

00:13:20.402 --> 00:13:23.505
discount rate of 2.51%,
you know how to convert that

00:13:23.505 --> 00:13:27.034
into the price and that's all
that matters--all that really

00:13:27.034 --> 00:13:29.590
matters is the price you have to
pay.

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:38.430
They also have something up
here called the investment rate.

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:40.468
Yes?
Student: I'm sorry,

00:13:40.468 --> 00:13:43.504
I don't understand since the
left hand side of your equation

00:13:43.504 --> 00:13:45.460
does not equal the right hand
side,

00:13:45.460 --> 00:13:48.202
isn't that discount, not price?
Professor Robert

00:13:48.202 --> 00:13:53.895
Shiller: I'm sorry,
glad you--that's the difference

00:13:53.895 --> 00:14:02.291
between 1 and 99.58.
Yes, thank you--between 100 and

00:14:02.291 --> 00:14:03.640
99.58.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:27.576
Are you okay now?
I'm sorry I made a--now the

00:14:27.576 --> 00:14:30.929
thing is, to convert that
into--what is this

00:14:30.929 --> 00:14:35.142
other--there's another interest
rate up here called the

00:14:35.142 --> 00:14:39.217
investment rate.
Well, that's supposed to be

00:14:39.217 --> 00:14:43.460
your percentage return on an
annualized basis.

00:14:43.460 --> 00:14:46.985
Remember, this thing only runs
for sixty days and you could

00:14:46.985 --> 00:14:50.611
compute your sixty-day return,
but people like to compare

00:14:50.611 --> 00:14:53.779
annual returns--once again,
a tradition we have.

00:14:53.779 --> 00:14:56.847
Now, there's nothing special
about annual--that's the time it

00:14:56.847 --> 00:14:58.789
take the Earth to go around the
sun,

00:14:58.789 --> 00:15:02.146
but it doesn't have any
relevance to finance--but we are

00:15:02.146 --> 00:15:06.538
just accustomed to using that.
What we're going to do,

00:15:06.538 --> 00:15:11.309
however, is take account of
another problem.

00:15:11.309 --> 00:15:21.673
That is, you might think that
this quantity here is my return

00:15:21.673 --> 00:15:30.309
but you have to actually divide
it by the price,

00:15:30.309 --> 00:15:33.340
which is less than a hundred,
to get a return.

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:37.159
You're not putting in $100 to
this investment;

00:15:37.159 --> 00:15:41.610
you're putting in $99.58 for
the investment and you're

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:46.059
getting out the difference
between $100 and $99.58.

00:15:46.059 --> 00:15:54.572
So, that is not--your return is
actually higher than 2.51% on an

00:15:54.572 --> 00:15:59.588
annualized basis.
What we do--I'll show you how

00:15:59.588 --> 00:16:01.530
they got their number.

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:15.744
2.563%, which is the number you
see under investment rate,

00:16:15.744 --> 00:16:24.961
is equal to 1/(.9958 –
1), corrected for the number of

00:16:24.961 --> 00:16:27.930
days in a year.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:38.448
How do we do that correction?
When I first tried this,

00:16:38.448 --> 00:16:45.345
I thought, fine I'll multiply
by 365/60, but I forgot this is

00:16:45.345 --> 00:16:53.840
a leap year.
So, times 366/60.

00:16:53.840 --> 00:17:03.357
So, that's how you go from the
discount rate to the investment

00:17:03.357 --> 00:17:06.085
rate.
Do you understand why we had to

00:17:06.085 --> 00:17:08.733
do this?
The investment rate is telling

00:17:08.733 --> 00:17:13.223
you how much money you're really
making on an annualized basis,

00:17:13.223 --> 00:17:19.514
so it's very simple.
I put in .9958 for every dollar

00:17:19.514 --> 00:17:27.569
I got out, so my appreciation of
my money is 1/.9958.

00:17:27.569 --> 00:17:30.687
Subtract that by $1,
which is what I put in,

00:17:30.687 --> 00:17:35.109
and that's how much money I
made as a fraction of a dollar.

00:17:35.109 --> 00:17:40.242
All I have to do then is
correct that for the number of

00:17:40.242 --> 00:17:43.950
days in a year,
so that's what I did.

00:17:43.950 --> 00:17:49.176
That's how we go from the
discount rate to the investment

00:17:49.176 --> 00:17:51.256
rate.
Now you might ask,

00:17:51.256 --> 00:17:55.456
well if we did 360 here,
why don't we just do 360 over

00:17:55.456 --> 00:17:57.692
here?
Well, it's one of the mysteries

00:17:57.692 --> 00:18:00.006
of Wall Street.
They like to--when they're

00:18:00.006 --> 00:18:03.265
computing the investment yield,
they want to be completely

00:18:03.265 --> 00:18:05.609
honest and not use any rules of
thumb.

00:18:05.609 --> 00:18:08.752
So you have to understand that
it's 360 a year because that's

00:18:08.752 --> 00:18:11.999
just a convention and everybody
knows that it's just the way we

00:18:11.999 --> 00:18:14.926
quote prices.
Rather than say $99.58,

00:18:14.926 --> 00:18:20.150
we just quote the 2.51 and
everybody knows how to convert.

00:18:20.150 --> 00:18:22.637
When you ask for the investment
rate, you want to know the

00:18:22.637 --> 00:18:25.081
truth--how much am I really
getting--so they don't monkey

00:18:25.081 --> 00:18:26.843
around here.
Also, they don't have to

00:18:26.843 --> 00:18:29.236
actually--in the old days,
they didn't actually have to

00:18:29.236 --> 00:18:32.170
compute the investment rate.
If you were talking to your

00:18:32.170 --> 00:18:35.521
broker--if you go really old
days, you'd send a boy running

00:18:35.521 --> 00:18:38.140
over to your broker.
They didn't have telephones;

00:18:38.140 --> 00:18:41.656
they used to have runners.
The boy would go say,

00:18:41.656 --> 00:18:46.276
we're offering to pay a
discount rate of 2.51--that was

00:18:46.276 --> 00:18:51.410
the formula--and then anyone
could do these calculations;

00:18:51.410 --> 00:18:56.399
they knew what it meant.
This calculation wasn't done

00:18:56.399 --> 00:19:00.047
very frequently;
that's just if you had one of

00:19:00.047 --> 00:19:03.240
the satisfactions of knowing how
much money you were making.

