Direct as an individual and buy
a Treasury bill,

00:20:05.619 --> 00:20:08.089
but it may not be the best
place to buy.

00:20:08.089 --> 00:20:12.581
What you normally do is you go
to a dealer and a dealer is

00:20:12.581 --> 00:20:16.974
someone, a professional,
who participated in the auction

00:20:16.974 --> 00:20:20.983
and bought these up to
accumulate an inventory to then

00:20:20.983 --> 00:20:23.349
sell off to you,
the customer.

00:20:23.349 --> 00:20:25.744
So normally,
you don't deal with Treasury

00:20:25.744 --> 00:20:29.936
Direct, you deal with a dealer.
The Wall Street Journal

00:20:29.936 --> 00:20:34.073
calls around to the dealer,
which has an inventory of all

00:20:34.073 --> 00:20:38.210
these maturities and asks them
for their bid and ask.

00:20:38.210 --> 00:20:43.283
And a dealer--what a dealer
does is it maintains an

00:20:43.283 --> 00:20:45.921
inventory of,
in this case,

00:20:45.921 --> 00:20:52.009
Treasury bills and then it
stands ready to buy and sell.

00:20:52.009 --> 00:20:55.900
So, the bid price is the--they
don't do it in terms of price,

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:59.207
they do it in terms of
discount--so the bid discount

00:20:59.207 --> 00:21:02.190
rate--there would be two numbers
for each.

00:21:02.190 --> 00:21:05.667
One is the bid,
which is what they'll pay you

00:21:05.667 --> 00:21:09.619
for a Treasury bill if you want
to sell to them.

00:21:09.619 --> 00:21:15.319
The ask is what you have to pay
them through this formula.

00:21:15.319 --> 00:21:23.843
The formula is--I could write
it this way: price equals one

00:21:23.843 --> 00:21:29.630
hundred minus this.
Normally, when you have a

00:21:29.630 --> 00:21:36.001
dealer, the dealer has a--when
we talk in terms of price the

00:21:36.001 --> 00:21:41.509
dealer has an ask,
which is higher than the bid.

00:21:41.509 --> 00:21:44.612
If you go to an antique
dealer--maybe you're familiar or

00:21:44.612 --> 00:21:47.827
maybe you've done this if you've
bought furniture for some

00:21:47.827 --> 00:21:52.049
apartment or something.
The dealer will charge a higher

00:21:52.049 --> 00:21:56.840
price for you to buy the
furniture than will give to you

00:21:56.840 --> 00:22:00.150
to purchase the furniture from
you;

00:22:00.150 --> 00:22:02.240
that's how the dealer makes a
difference.

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:06.499
The difference between bid and
ask is the profit for the dealer

00:22:06.499 --> 00:22:10.210
and the bid-ask spread is the
profit for the dealer.

00:22:10.210 --> 00:22:14.521
You can see these--you can see
the bid and ask in The Wall

00:22:14.521 --> 00:22:18.099
Street Journal.
It's interesting to look at it

00:22:18.099 --> 00:22:20.859
because you note that the
bid-ask spread,

00:22:20.859 --> 00:22:24.862
which is the difference between
the bid and the ask for the

00:22:24.862 --> 00:22:28.108
dealer,
is narrower in the more liquid

00:22:28.108 --> 00:22:32.543
securities and some of the
securities that are small and

00:22:32.543 --> 00:22:35.930
unimportant have a wide bid-ask
spread.

00:22:35.930 --> 00:22:38.677
That means that it's harder to
make a market for it,

00:22:38.677 --> 00:22:40.670
so the dealer wants to charge
more.

00:22:40.670 --> 00:22:46.094
This doesn't show this here.
Unfortunately,

00:22:46.094 --> 00:22:50.022
The Wall Street Journal
stopped carrying this and I

00:22:50.022 --> 00:22:53.950
thought--it's an interesting
story about what goes on.

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:58.912
The Wall Street Journal
is the most influential

00:22:58.912 --> 00:23:04.343
financial publication in this
country but it has been going

00:23:04.343 --> 00:23:09.680
