00:29:15.539 --> 00:29:19.288
Online is not free.
Anyway, I want to talk--you

00:29:19.288 --> 00:29:22.630
understand now about discount
bonds?

00:29:22.630 --> 00:29:25.962
It's pretty simple, right?
I just wanted to get the

00:29:25.962 --> 00:29:28.833
pricing formula.
The critical thing about a

00:29:28.833 --> 00:29:31.059
discount bond is it pays no
interest.

00:29:31.059 --> 00:29:36.633
Treasury bills in the United
States are limited to one year

00:29:36.633 --> 00:29:38.859
out;
well, that's the name of it.

00:29:38.859 --> 00:29:44.779
We call an instrument of the
U.S.

00:29:44.779 --> 00:29:49.626
Treasury with a maturity less
than or equal to one year--we

00:29:49.626 --> 00:29:54.639
call that a bill--and they used
to be the only discount bonds

00:29:54.639 --> 00:29:57.480
issued by the U.S.
Government.

00:29:57.480 --> 00:30:02.257
Now, they also have longer
maturity, called Treasury

00:30:02.257 --> 00:30:05.910
strips, but let me move to the
other.

00:30:05.910 --> 00:30:10.434
So we have--U.S.
Government issues bills and

00:30:10.434 --> 00:30:16.420
that's less than or equal to one
year and they pay no interest.

00:30:16.420 --> 00:30:21.161
They also have
government-issued notes and

00:30:21.161 --> 00:30:27.058
that's from one to ten years and
bonds--this is just

00:30:27.058 --> 00:30:35.289
jargon--these are ten or more,
well actually more than ten.

00:30:35.289 --> 00:30:42.173
I'll show you from Treasury
Direct--I have notes--this

00:30:42.173 --> 00:30:50.595
should be greater than ten.
These are the recent auctions

00:30:50.595 --> 00:30:57.089
of the Treasury of notes.
Now, these are different from

00:30:57.089 --> 00:31:01.170
bills, as I emphasized,
because they pay interest.

00:31:01.170 --> 00:31:03.320
They carry what's called a
coupon.

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:14.751
And then we have the bonds.
You see there aren't as many of

00:31:14.751 --> 00:31:17.120
these issued.
We issue a lot of–there

00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:19.899
are a lot of auctions of
Treasury bills and there are

00:31:19.899 --> 00:31:21.610
comparatively fewer of bonds.

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:37.256
So, let's talk about a bond.
A bond differs from a bill in

00:31:37.256 --> 00:31:44.673
that it carries what's called a
coupon, which I will denote by

00:31:44.673 --> 00:31:51.960
the letter C,
and it has a principal,

00:31:51.960 --> 00:32:00.940
which it pays out at the
end--of one hundred.

00:32:00.940 --> 00:32:05.273
Of course, there would be
larger denominations than $100,

00:32:05.273 --> 00:32:08.677
but by tradition,
we speak of them as if they

00:32:08.677 --> 00:32:11.849
were bonds that you paid $100 to
get.

00:32:11.849 --> 00:32:21.321
Now, another Wall Street
tradition is that bonds pay a

00:32:21.321 --> 00:32:28.894
coupon;
they pay C/2 every six

00:32:28.894 --> 00:32:30.540
months.

00:32:35.849 --> 00:32:38.480
The coupon is expressed as an
annual amount;

00:32:38.480 --> 00:32:41.059
you get half of it every six
months.

00:32:41.059 --> 00:32:45.612
The reason they call them
coupons is that,

00:32:45.612 --> 00:32:50.721
in the old days,
you used to actually--when you

00:32:50.721 --> 00:32:54.542
bought a bond,
there would be a piece of paper

00:32:54.542 --> 00:32:57.835
and the piece of paper would
have attached to it a lot of

00:32:57.835 --> 00:33:00.069
little coupons that you would
clip.

00:33:00.069 --> 00:33:04.052
If it was a twenty-year bond,
there would be forty coupons,

00:33:04.052 --> 00:33:08.173
one for each six-month period,
and each one would have a date

00:33:08.173 --> 00:33:10.119
on it.
What you used to do is,

00:33:10.119 --> 00:33:13.403
every six months you'd pull out
your bonds and you'd clip the

00:33:13.403 --> 00:33:17.425
coupons with a pair of scissors;
you take them to a bank and

00:33:17.425 --> 00:33:20.779
they would give you cash for
your coupons.

00:33:20.779 --> 00:33:24.844
So, we still call them coupons,
but now we don't do it--we do

00:33:24.844 --> 00:33:27.931
things electronically.
You don't have to clip coupons

00:33:27.931 --> 00:33:30.647
anymore.
If you want to see bonds as

00:33:30.647 --> 00:33:33.767
they used to look,
with their coupons,

00:33:33.767 --> 00:33:38.574
there are a number of them at
the International Center for

00:33:38.574 --> 00:33:42.960
Finance down the street here
with their coupons still

00:33:42.960 --> 00:33:46.123
attached.
So they've got a lot of--Will

00:33:46.123 --> 00:33:50.000
Goetzmann and Geert Rouwenhorst
are collectors of old bonds and

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:53.940
they've got lots of bonds with
their coupons still attached.

00:33:53.940 --> 00:33:56.461
You know what that means when
they're framed there on the wall

00:33:56.461 --> 00:33:57.950
with their coupons still
attached?

00:33:57.950 --> 00:34:01.109
It means the company went
bankrupt and never paid;

00:34:01.109 --> 00:34:03.869
otherwise, the coupons would
have been clipped.

00:34:03.869 --> 00:34:07.761
It's actually--our
International Center for Finance

00:34:07.761 --> 00:34:11.030
is sort of a museum for
defaulted bonds.

00:34:11.030 --> 00:34:14.488
The ones that are beautiful for
framing are the ones that

00:34:14.488 --> 00:34:17.019
failed, so you can see all the
coupons.

00:34:17.019 --> 00:34:19.920
Some of them have some of the
coupons clipped and then they

00:34:19.920 --> 00:34:22.670
stop and you know that it was
bad news when they stopped

00:34:22.670 --> 00:34:25.820
clipping them.
We still call them coupons.

00:34:25.820 --> 00:34:32.031
If you have a bond with an
interest rate of 4.375%--that's

00:34:32.031 --> 00:34:38.352
not an easy one to divide by
two--but you would get half of

00:34:38.352 --> 00:34:42.820
that every six months until
maturity.

00:34:42.820 --> 00:34:49.863
We have to ask then,
how do we get the price and the

00:34:49.863 --> 00:34:52.350
yield from this?

00:34:55.489 --> 00:34:58.427
What we do is we take the
interest rate,

00:34:58.427 --> 00:35:02.570
which I'll call r,
and plug it into a formula,

00:35:02.570 --> 00:35:11.643
which I didn't actually do the
arithmetic to check--to check

00:35:11.643 --> 00:35:19.252
their number.
The price is just the present

00:35:19.252 --> 00:35:28.760
value of the coupons at the
interest rate r,

00:35:28.760 --> 00:35:36.144
so the price of a bond is the
present discounted value of

00:35:36.144 --> 00:35:45.020
coupons and principal,
at rate r.

00:35:48.969 --> 00:35:51.799
Now, you have to understand
that when you buy a bond,

00:35:51.799 --> 00:35:55.283
if you buy it at issue,
you get the first coupon in six

00:35:55.283 --> 00:35:59.188
months, the second coupon in one
year, the third coupon in

00:35:59.188 --> 00:36:03.269
eighteen months,
and the last coupon you get at

00:36:03.269 --> 00:36:07.110
the maturity date.
So that means--what is the

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:11.363
stream of payments?
You get C/2 in six

00:36:11.363 --> 00:36:17.093
months, C/2 again in a
year, C/2 again in

00:36:17.093 --> 00:36:23.388
eighteen months,
and that continues until the

00:36:23.388 --> 00:36:31.639
last date--the maturity
date--when you get 100 + C/2.

00:36:31.639 --> 00:36:38.401
The price is just the present
value of that stream,

00:36:38.401 --> 00:36:43.000
discounted at the interest
rate.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:37:03.370
The formula can also be written
and expanded out--P =

00:37:03.370 --> 00:37:20.606
(c/2) x
[(1/(r/2)--which is the

00:37:20.606 --> 00:37:34.459
consol formula,
if this were applied to an

00:37:34.459 --> 00:37:45.306
infinite stream-- -
1/(1+(r/2))^(2T) x

00:37:45.306 --> 00:37:57.811
1/(r/2)].
Let me make sure I've got this

00:37:57.811 --> 00:38:07.980
right-- +100
(1/(1+(r/2))^(2T).

00:38:07.980 --> 00:38:11.868
This should be obvious--if I
did that right--this should be

00:38:11.868 --> 00:38:16.159
obvious from what you learned
about in present value formulas.

00:38:16.159 --> 00:38:21.371
If you had a perpetuity,
which paid C/2 forever,

00:38:21.371 --> 00:38:26.390
you already know from the
perpetuity formula that the

00:38:26.390 --> 00:38:31.602
value of that would be
C/2 divided by r/2

00:38:31.602 --> 00:38:35.559
if r/2 is the discount
rate.

00:38:35.559 --> 00:38:42.551
It's not forever because it
terminates after 2T periods of

00:38:42.551 --> 00:38:48.862
six-month interval each.
You want to subtract off the

00:38:48.862 --> 00:38:53.545
value of a perpetuity that
starts after 2T,

00:38:53.545 --> 00:38:59.387
six-month intervals,
so this is the present value of

00:38:59.387 --> 00:39:05.519
the perpetuity that starts after
2T, six-month intervals.

00:39:05.519 --> 00:39:09.908
Then you want to add the
present value of the principal

00:39:09.908 --> 00:39:14.681
and that's the formula.
That's another conventional

00:39:14.681 --> 00:39:21.080
formula that goes from interest
rate to price of the security.

00:39:39.309 --> 00:39:45.098
Now, I want to talk about the
term structure of interest rates

00:39:45.098 --> 00:39:51.722
and that's my next plot here.
That's the term structure as of

00:39:51.722 --> 00:39:59.878
now on the chart.
We've identified the prices and

00:39:59.878 --> 00:40:07.449
yields of bonds of various
maturities.

00:40:07.449 --> 00:40:15.269
How do the prices and yields
look at various points in time?

00:40:15.269 --> 00:40:18.929
So, I've got here a term
structure;

00:40:18.929 --> 00:40:26.911
well, the term structure is the
plot of yield-to-maturity

00:40:26.911 --> 00:40:33.049
against time-to-maturity.
This is January of this year,

00:40:33.049 --> 00:40:37.313
before the Fed cut interest
rates, and this is the term

00:40:37.313 --> 00:40:40.476
structure.
I've got the Federal Funds

00:40:40.476 --> 00:40:45.652
Rate--it's the shortest interest
rate, an overnight rate--it was

00:40:45.652 --> 00:40:50.090
at 4% at that time and then
there was a sharp drop.

00:40:50.090 --> 00:40:53.608
The three-month Treasury bill
rate is shown there--it was much

00:40:53.608 --> 00:40:57.564
lower--it was under 3%.
Then the--so the term structure

00:40:57.564 --> 00:41:02.755
was downward-sloping until about
two and a half years and then it

00:41:02.755 --> 00:41:06.409
was upward sloping.
The interesting question from

00:41:06.409 --> 00:41:10.083
the standpoint of economic
theory is, why did it have that

00:41:10.083 --> 00:41:15.123
funny shape?
I want to compare it with other

00:41:15.123 --> 00:41:20.510
examples of the term structure
recently.

00:41:20.510 --> 00:41:25.891
This is the term structure just
a short while ago--of December

00:41:25.891 --> 00:41:30.926
2006--very different.
The Federal Funds Rate was 5.5%

00:41:30.926 --> 00:41:36.065
and then the whole term
structure--all the way--almost

00:41:36.065 --> 00:41:39.781
all the way.
Well, there's this funny glitch

00:41:39.781 --> 00:41:43.719
here between three-month and
one-year, but then it just

00:41:43.719 --> 00:41:46.653
continued to decline.
That's a strongly

00:41:46.653 --> 00:41:51.173
downward-sloping term structure.
This is another example,

00:41:51.173 --> 00:41:54.880
not so long ago--this is
December 2003.

00:41:54.880 --> 00:41:59.087
Now, the term structure was
pretty much upward-sloping

00:41:59.087 --> 00:42:01.222
everywhere.
At that time,

00:42:01.222 --> 00:42:04.952
the Fed had cut the Federal
Funds Rate to 1%,

00:42:04.952 --> 00:42:09.880
we had very low short rates.
And the three-month Treasury

00:42:09.880 --> 00:42:12.920
bill rate was about the same,
at 1%.

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:16.658
Going further out,
the term structure just kept

00:42:16.658 --> 00:42:19.301
rising.
It's one of the questions of

00:42:19.301 --> 00:42:22.510
economics--what determines the
term structure?

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:25.849
You have to understand that
it's determined in the market.

00:42:25.849 --> 00:42:30.580
The Fed has these auctions but
it auctions them off at what

00:42:30.580 --> 00:42:34.984
price the public will pay,
so the Fed doesn't determine

00:42:34.984 --> 00:42:38.146
the term structure.
Neither do the dealers

00:42:38.146 --> 00:42:41.610
determine the term structure;
the dealers have to buy and

00:42:41.610 --> 00:42:44.079
sell at prices that are in the
market.

00:42:44.079 --> 00:42:47.373
It has to stay relevant to the
market, so nobody really knows

00:42:47.373 --> 00:42:50.776
where these interest rates come
from because no one person sets

00:42:50.776 --> 00:42:52.514
them.
If you're a dealer,

00:42:52.514 --> 00:42:55.329
you've got to keep your bid-ask
at market;

00:42:55.329 --> 00:42:58.407
otherwise, you'll get only one
side or the other,

00:42:58.407 --> 00:43:00.926
right?
You'll be selling too cheaply

00:43:00.926 --> 00:43:04.576
or you'll be buying too dearly.
You've got to do it so you're

00:43:04.576 --> 00:43:06.954
right in the middle,
so that the market is in the

00:43:06.954 --> 00:43:09.420
middle.
Nobody really sees the reason

00:43:09.420 --> 00:43:13.158
for this;
it's all a question of theory,

00:43:13.158 --> 00:43:17.949
so we have to think a little
bit about theory.

00:43:17.949 --> 00:43:23.791
The term structure is one of
the most interesting things in

00:43:23.791 --> 00:43:29.229
economics because it shows the
price of time at various

00:43:29.229 --> 00:43:34.867
maturities.
In 2003, time was almost free

00:43:34.867 --> 00:43:39.092
out three months.
It didn't--if you needed more

00:43:39.092 --> 00:43:42.016
time to get some business done
you'd have to borrow,

00:43:42.016 --> 00:43:44.309
but you'd only have to pay 1% a
year.

00:43:44.309 --> 00:43:48.796
That would be like a quarter of
1% to postpone your payment by

00:43:48.796 --> 00:43:51.699
another year;
so time was really cheap.

00:43:51.699 --> 00:43:55.695
But if you wanted to postpone
it over seven years or so,

00:43:55.695 --> 00:44:00.146
time got a lot more expensive.
Why is this and why is the

00:44:00.146 --> 00:44:06.282
price of time changing?
One thing to do is to go back

00:44:06.282 --> 00:44:13.619
and ask, what really are the
reasons for interest?

00:44:13.619 --> 00:44:22.360
I wanted to talk about the
theory of interest as presented

00:44:22.360 --> 00:44:31.406
by Professor Irving Fisher at
Yale, who is famous for having

00:44:31.406 --> 00:44:37.459
exposited that.
I imagine he did it at this

00:44:37.459 --> 00:44:43.854
very blackboard because,
as I said, he had his office in

00:44:43.854 --> 00:44:49.320
this building and he didn't die
until 1940s,

00:44:49.320 --> 00:44:51.679
so he must have been--this
building was--this room goes

00:44:51.679 --> 00:44:54.122
back to the '30s.
He had a diagram,

00:44:54.122 --> 00:44:59.434
which illustrated what is the
ultimate cause of interest,

00:44:59.434 --> 00:45:05.220
and it helps us to think about
this diagram whenever we try to

00:45:05.220 --> 00:45:14.034
understand the term structure.
What his diagram--this is the

00:45:14.034 --> 00:45:21.234
famous Irving Fisher
diagram--depicted,

00:45:21.234 --> 00:45:29.750
there's only one period;
there's today on this axis and

00:45:29.750 --> 00:45:34.849
tomorrow–well,
I shouldn't say tomorrow,

00:45:34.849 --> 00:45:40.630
that suggests one day--next
period on this axis.

00:45:40.630 --> 00:45:46.838
Let's say it's one year and I'm
going to actually plot on this

00:45:46.838 --> 00:45:50.400
axis a person's income this
year.

00:45:50.400 --> 00:45:59.723
I should say income today on
this axis and on this,

00:45:59.723 --> 00:46:05.626
income next period.
So for each person,

00:46:05.626 --> 00:46:11.691
there is a point representing
my income today and my income

00:46:11.691 --> 00:46:14.559
next period.
Let's assume that I know what

00:46:14.559 --> 00:46:17.344
I'm earning next year;
there is actually uncertainty

00:46:17.344 --> 00:46:20.933
about it.
If I draw this down this--this

00:46:20.933 --> 00:46:27.299
point is this year's income down
here and this point here is next

00:46:27.299 --> 00:46:33.969
year's income;
I'll use Y for income.

00:46:33.969 --> 00:46:37.780
This is Y today and this
is Y next period.

00:46:37.780 --> 00:46:43.058
A person has a budget
constraint if the person can

00:46:43.058 --> 00:46:47.260
borrow and lend at the interest
rate.

00:46:47.260 --> 00:46:55.966
The budget constraint is a
straight line through this point

00:46:55.966 --> 00:47:01.970
with a slope of (1+r).
I'll try to draw this line.

00:47:06.770 --> 00:47:09.623
That should be a straight line.
It doesn't look that straight

00:47:09.623 --> 00:47:11.570
because I was running out of
room up here.

00:47:11.570 --> 00:47:19.288
You see, that's a straight line.
This point here then is the

00:47:19.288 --> 00:47:29.087
present value of your income;
it's (Y _today

00:47:29.087 --> 00:47:36.060
+ Y _next
period) / (1 + r).

00:47:36.060 --> 00:47:43.982
What's this point up here?
This point up here is the

00:47:43.982 --> 00:47:52.320
terminal value of my income,
so the upper point is (Y

00:47:52.320 --> 00:48:01.929
_today *(1 + r)
+ Y _next year.

00:48:01.929 --> 00:48:05.532
In an ideal world,
where you can borrow and lend

00:48:05.532 --> 00:48:09.747
freely, an individual could
choose consumption along any

00:48:09.747 --> 00:48:13.179
point on this line.
I could consume all of my

00:48:13.179 --> 00:48:16.117
income--if I borrow against my
future income,

00:48:16.117 --> 00:48:19.389
I could--there's a problem here
of starvation.

00:48:19.389 --> 00:48:22.630
If I consume it all this year,
I will be starving.

00:48:22.630 --> 00:48:25.420
I don't see how I can earn
income next year but,

00:48:25.420 --> 00:48:28.210
in principle,
that's what Irving Fisher said.

00:48:28.210 --> 00:48:31.104
Well, I could just not consume
anything this year and I could

00:48:31.104 --> 00:48:33.710
wait until next year and consume
the terminal value.

00:48:33.710 --> 00:48:37.422
I would take my income this
year, invest it at the interest

00:48:37.422 --> 00:48:41.262
rate, and it would turn into
Y today times (1 + R) and

00:48:41.262 --> 00:48:44.949
then I get income next year;
so I could consume all that.

00:48:44.949 --> 00:48:47.909
I can consume at any point
along that line as well.

00:48:47.909 --> 00:48:50.935
I could consume at today's
income, or I could consume here,

00:48:50.935 --> 00:48:54.292
or I consume down here.
If I consume less than my

00:48:54.292 --> 00:48:57.741
income today,
I'm saving and my consumption

00:48:57.741 --> 00:49:02.679
would be lower this year.
Am I doing that right?

00:49:02.679 --> 00:49:06.922
No, if I'm saving this year my
consumption would be less than

00:49:06.922 --> 00:49:11.023
my income, so my consumption
might be here and I would then

00:49:11.023 --> 00:49:15.458
have more next year.
Each individual reaches a

00:49:15.458 --> 00:49:22.032
decision--each individual has an
income point and decides how

00:49:22.032 --> 00:49:27.510
much to consume based on the
budget constraint.

00:49:27.510 --> 00:49:32.213
Now, the interest rate in
Irving Fisher's world has to

00:49:32.213 --> 00:49:36.650
equate supply and demand in the
market for debt.

00:49:36.650 --> 00:49:42.093
Each person who wants to borrow
has to be met by somebody else

00:49:42.093 --> 00:49:46.198
who wants to lend,
so the interest rate that we

00:49:46.198 --> 00:49:49.590
have in society is the
compromise.

00:49:49.590 --> 00:49:55.521
It's the interest rate that
clears the market for loans and

00:49:55.521 --> 00:50:01.349
that interest rate determines
the market interest rate.

00:50:01.349 --> 00:50:06.250
Nobody can see the interest
rate--why the interest rate's at

00:50:06.250 --> 00:50:10.570
the level it is in the
market--because nobody can see

00:50:10.570 --> 00:50:16.110
all these individuals;
but that's why the interest

00:50:16.110 --> 00:50:21.619
rate gets determined and is in
equilibrium.

00:50:21.619 --> 00:50:24.830
Why the interest rate
clears--it's a mysterious

00:50:24.830 --> 00:50:28.458
phenomenon, because it's a
market phenomenon and each

00:50:28.458 --> 00:50:32.715
person only sees his or her own
contribution to the market and

00:50:32.715 --> 00:50:36.763
not the whole market.
Irving Fisher also drew on the

00:50:36.763 --> 00:50:40.440
curve a production possibility
frontier for society,

00:50:40.440 --> 00:50:45.836
which he made downward-curved.
This is production possibility

00:50:45.836 --> 00:50:51.166
frontier and that is a
curve--you've seen these before

00:50:51.166 --> 00:50:57.200
in economics--that says how the
production of our society can

00:50:57.200 --> 00:51:03.033
produce different combinations
of income this year and next

00:51:03.033 --> 00:51:05.753
year.
If there were no credit

00:51:05.753 --> 00:51:09.900
markets, everyone would have to
be on the production possibility

00:51:09.900 --> 00:51:12.260
frontier;
there would be no other choice.

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:16.537
But if we have credit markets,
then people can individually

00:51:16.537 --> 00:51:20.961
choose to be off the production
possibility frontier and at a

00:51:20.961 --> 00:51:24.869
higher level of consumption than
otherwise would.

00:51:24.869 --> 00:51:29.324
You might have some people up
here who are saving and other

00:51:29.324 --> 00:51:33.318
people down here who are
dissaving and the production

00:51:33.318 --> 00:51:36.159
would be operating at the
middle.

00:51:36.159 --> 00:51:42.370
So, that is Irving Fisher's
diagram in a nutshell,

00:51:42.370 --> 00:51:50.610
but I think it's--so what does
it say about the term structure?

00:51:50.610 --> 00:51:53.833
It says that at different
horizons everything on this

00:51:53.833 --> 00:51:56.948
diagram is different.
The production possibility

00:51:56.948 --> 00:52:00.519
frontier at different horizons
is in different places.

00:52:00.519 --> 00:52:04.687
The budget constraint is going
to have a different slope to it

00:52:04.687 --> 00:52:08.102
and preferences will be
different over this horizon

00:52:08.102 --> 00:52:11.449
between consumption then and
consumption now.

00:52:11.449 --> 00:52:15.502
So you--it doesn't--this theory
doesn't say a whole lot about

00:52:15.502 --> 00:52:19.419
what the term structure will
look like but it suggests that

00:52:19.419 --> 00:52:23.810
it's determined by the interplay
of lots of economic factors.

00:52:35.010 --> 00:52:39.371
I want to talk about a couple
of other basic concepts in

00:52:39.371 --> 00:52:44.687
economics of interest rates.
One of them is the forward rate

00:52:44.687 --> 00:52:49.900
and the other one is inflation
indexed interest rates.

00:52:49.900 --> 00:52:57.677
Forward rates--I wrote a survey
article years ago about the term

00:52:57.677 --> 00:53:05.454
structure of interest rates and
I wanted to find out who was the

00:53:05.454 --> 00:53:10.639
originator of the term "forward
rate."

00:53:10.639 --> 00:53:14.617
I asked my graduate student
research assistant to research

00:53:14.617 --> 00:53:18.734
the whole literature and find
out where did the word forward

00:53:18.734 --> 00:53:22.318
rate come from.
My graduate student came back

00:53:22.318 --> 00:53:27.147
and said, it seems to have been
Sir John Hicks in London in his

00:53:27.147 --> 00:53:30.730
1931--1939 book,
A Value in Capital.

00:53:38.370 --> 00:53:42.815
This is another aside.
but I think it's motivational,

00:53:42.815 --> 00:53:45.342
and so I said,
are you sure that J.R.

00:53:45.342 --> 00:53:48.290
Hicks invented the term
"forward rate"?

00:53:48.290 --> 00:53:51.018
He said, how can I be sure?
I mean, I've looked through

00:53:51.018 --> 00:53:52.699
everything;
I can't find any earlier

00:53:52.699 --> 00:53:54.375
reference.
And he said,

00:53:54.375 --> 00:53:56.739
I think it's J.R.
Hicks.

00:53:56.739 --> 00:54:00.186
Then, I was talking it over
with another graduate student

00:54:00.186 --> 00:54:04.064
and he said, well if you want to
find out why don't you ask J.R.

00:54:04.064 --> 00:54:06.326
Hicks?
And I said, wait a minute,

00:54:06.326 --> 00:54:09.690
is that guy still alive?
He said, I think he is.

00:54:09.690 --> 00:54:13.880
I found out he was living in
London--Lord Hicks;

00:54:13.880 --> 00:54:17.360
I guess he got knighted for his
contribution.

00:54:17.360 --> 00:54:20.403
I wrote him a letter and I
said, basically,

00:54:20.403 --> 00:54:24.795
did you invent forward rates?
Then, I didn't get any response

00:54:24.795 --> 00:54:28.395
for like three months and then
to my surprise I got a

00:54:28.395 --> 00:54:31.303
hand-written letter,
in kind of a trembling

00:54:31.303 --> 00:54:34.469
handwriting;
I still have it.

00:54:34.469 --> 00:54:36.769
I should--I can put it up on
the screen actually.

00:54:36.769 --> 00:54:44.980
He said, my apologies--he was
very polite and diplomatic.

00:54:44.980 --> 00:54:48.948
He said, my apologies for not
answering your letter but my

00:54:48.948 --> 00:54:52.219
health is poor and--but it was a
long letter.

00:54:52.219 --> 00:54:55.669
He said, I'm trying to remember
where I got the idea and,

00:54:55.669 --> 00:54:59.118
he said, I think it probably
came from some of our coffee

00:54:59.118 --> 00:55:02.630
hours at The London School of
Economics in the 1920s.

00:55:02.630 --> 00:55:05.909
He said, we were discussing
that, and then he said,

00:55:05.909 --> 00:55:09.845
I thought it was in a book that
my wife and I translated from

00:55:09.845 --> 00:55:13.387
the Swedish in the 1930s but,
he said, I've looked and it's

00:55:13.387 --> 00:55:15.487
not there.
So he said, I guess maybe it is

00:55:15.487 --> 00:55:17.929
my idea--I was the first person
to write it up.

00:55:17.929 --> 00:55:22.207
Then he died shortly
thereafter, so I got to him just

00:55:22.207 --> 00:55:25.512
in time.
I thought I would describe

00:55:25.512 --> 00:55:31.336
forward rates in terms of the
coffee hour at The London School

00:55:31.336 --> 00:55:35.243
of Economics in the '20s.
This is J.R.

00:55:35.243 --> 00:55:41.207
Hicks talking--so the year is
1925--and we're talking about

00:55:41.207 --> 00:55:47.889
investing in discount bonds and
we're going to put £100.

00:55:47.889 --> 00:55:54.940
Now suppose--the idea that
Hicks invented is that they're,

00:55:54.940 --> 00:56:02.609
implicit in the term structure,
there are future interest rates

00:56:02.609 --> 00:56:07.070
already quoted.
I showed you the term structure.

00:56:07.070 --> 00:56:11.056
I showed you a one-year
Treasury bill rate for right

00:56:11.056 --> 00:56:14.965
now--that's not right now,
but you can see I have a

00:56:14.965 --> 00:56:18.639
one-year and a two-year Treasury
bill rate.

00:56:18.639 --> 00:56:22.665
The idea of a forward rate is
that, implicit in that term

00:56:22.665 --> 00:56:26.260
structure is also a quote for
the one-year rate,

00:56:26.260 --> 00:56:29.062
one year hence,
because if you look at the

00:56:29.062 --> 00:56:31.727
two-year rate,
can't you infer back what

00:56:31.727 --> 00:56:34.940
interest rates are going to be
in one year?

00:56:34.940 --> 00:56:39.604
Because the two-year rate
is--you've got the one-year rate

00:56:39.604 --> 00:56:42.550
and the two rate,
so between the two,

00:56:42.550 --> 00:56:45.225
what's left?
The difference between those

00:56:45.225 --> 00:56:47.908
two somehow reflects what
interest rates will be between

00:56:47.908 --> 00:56:50.377
one and two.
What Hicks said--this is the

00:56:50.377 --> 00:56:54.163
coffee hour conversation at The
London School of Economics--he

00:56:54.163 --> 00:56:57.870
said,
it's right now 1925 but if you

00:56:57.870 --> 00:57:03.650
want to invest or borrow in 1926
I can do it for you.

00:57:03.650 --> 00:57:07.590
I can lock in the interest rate
right now.

00:57:07.590 --> 00:57:15.827
So let's say,
okay I expect--suppose I expect

00:57:15.827 --> 00:57:22.035
to get £100 in 1926.
Here we are,

00:57:22.035 --> 00:57:24.447
sitting in 1925,
and I want to,

00:57:24.447 --> 00:57:27.906
today in 1925,
lock in the investment return

00:57:27.906 --> 00:57:32.329
that I will get when I invest
that hundred pounds.

00:57:32.329 --> 00:57:38.978
So, what we want to do--this is
what Hicks discovered--I can do

00:57:38.978 --> 00:57:43.159
the following transaction to
lock in,

00:57:43.159 --> 00:57:49.650
in 1925, the interest rate
between 1926 and 1927.

00:57:49.650 --> 00:57:56.112
Here we are sitting in 1925;
I'm going to buy in '25 this

00:57:56.112 --> 00:58:03.165
amount of two-period bonds--two
year-bonds--(1 +

00:58:03.165 --> 00:58:11.870
r_2)²/(1 +
r_1).

00:58:18.400 --> 00:58:27.655
These will mature and be worth
£100 in '26 and I'm going

00:58:27.655 --> 00:58:34.644
to short how much?
I'm going to short one

00:58:34.644 --> 00:58:37.700
one-period bond.

00:58:45.719 --> 00:58:52.582
This is the number of bonds I
have to buy and so let's analyze

00:58:52.582 --> 00:58:56.435
this.
That's all I have to do and I

00:58:56.435 --> 00:59:00.030
have locked in the interest
rate.

00:59:00.030 --> 00:59:04.329
r_1 is the
yield on the one-period bond and

00:59:04.329 --> 00:59:08.630
r_2 is the
yield on the two-period bond.

00:59:08.630 --> 00:59:12.507
The price of the two-period
bond is 1/(1 +

00:59:12.507 --> 00:59:17.992
r_2)²
and the price of the one-period

00:59:17.992 --> 00:59:21.869
bond is 1/(1 +
r_1).

00:59:21.869 --> 00:59:26.789
If I buy this amount of
two-period bonds,

00:59:26.789 --> 00:59:31.716
how much does it cost me?
It costs me 1/(1 +

00:59:31.716 --> 00:59:37.666
r_1).
If I short the one-period bond

00:59:37.666 --> 00:59:43.640
it cancels out,
so I've made no net purchase in

00:59:43.640 --> 00:59:47.134
1925.
I bought a number of two-period

00:59:47.134 --> 00:59:51.726
bonds such that the value of my
purchase exactly equals the

00:59:51.726 --> 00:59:56.239
proceeds that I get from
shorting the one period bond,

00:59:56.239 --> 00:59:59.559
so I've made a zero wealth
transaction.

00:59:59.559 --> 01:00:04.652
It hasn't affected my
portfolio--my cash position--at

01:00:04.652 --> 01:00:09.373
all.
What happens then in--that's in

01:00:09.373 --> 01:00:14.440
1925, so there's no cash flow at
all.

01:00:19.180 --> 01:00:23.756
In '26, what happens?
Well, in '26,

01:00:23.756 --> 01:00:28.919
the--I've shorted the
one-period bond and so I have to

01:00:28.919 --> 01:00:33.206
pay out one dollar,
but that's exactly what I

01:00:33.206 --> 01:00:37.386
wanted to do.
Remember, I said I'm doing this

01:00:37.386 --> 01:00:41.457
because I expect to have a
hundred pounds--I said one

01:00:41.457 --> 01:00:46.154
dollar--I'm going to have to pay
out a hundred pounds because

01:00:46.154 --> 01:00:49.720
this one-period bond,
worth one hundred pounds

01:00:49.720 --> 01:00:52.909
principal, is coming due so I
have to pay it out.

01:00:52.909 --> 01:00:55.499
That's what I wanted to do
because I said I'd have a

01:00:55.499 --> 01:00:59.295
hundred pounds to invest.
Nothing happens to the

01:00:59.295 --> 01:01:05.139
two-period bond because it just
continues to mature.

01:01:05.139 --> 01:01:13.540
So 1926, I pay one hundred
pounds.

01:01:13.540 --> 01:01:22.354
What happens in 1927?
Now what happens is,

01:01:22.354 --> 01:01:26.730
I now get the maturity of this
bond.

01:01:26.730 --> 01:01:35.169
What I get--I have purchased
this number of bonds,

01:01:35.169 --> 01:01:46.019
so I'm going to get a hundred
pounds times that amount there,

01:01:46.019 --> 01:01:50.516
the number of bonds--(1 +
r_2)²/(1 +

01:01:50.516 --> 01:01:55.347
r_1).
You can see that by doing this

01:01:55.347 --> 01:02:01.320
transaction I have locked in a
return between 1926 and 1927.

01:02:01.320 --> 01:02:05.469
I did it in 1925,
but I've got it set up so that

01:02:05.469 --> 01:02:11.119
I will pay a hundred pounds in
1926 and I'll get this in 1927.

01:02:11.119 --> 01:02:18.175
He calls the forward rate equal
to (1 +

01:02:18.175 --> 01:02:28.760
r_2)²/(1 +
r_1).

01:02:28.760 --> 01:02:32.648
This is Hicks's discovery.
You might say,

01:02:32.648 --> 01:02:35.046
this should have been obvious
to someone, but it had never

01:02:35.046 --> 01:02:37.827
been written up well before.
What Hicks said is that in

01:02:37.827 --> 01:02:40.612
these term structures,
you don't just have today's

01:02:40.612 --> 01:02:43.340
interest rates--this is a
map–actually,

01:02:43.340 --> 01:02:45.976
I've just showed the
one-period, he had one-period

01:02:45.976 --> 01:02:49.258
forward rate--but you could do
it over any combination and you

01:02:49.258 --> 01:02:52.539
can get forward rates of any
maturity at any future date.

01:02:52.539 --> 01:02:59.394
That's Hicks's insight and it
comes back then to Hicks's book,

01:02:59.394 --> 01:03:03.440
Value and Capital,
in 1939.

01:03:03.440 --> 01:03:07.865
He said that we shouldn't think
that the--the simplest story of

01:03:07.865 --> 01:03:10.650
the term structure of interest
rates,

01:03:10.650 --> 01:03:13.745
which he expounded there,
is that forward rates equal

01:03:13.745 --> 01:03:17.319
expected future interest rates.
That means, in the

01:03:17.319 --> 01:03:22.327
simplest--it's called the
expectations theory of the term

01:03:22.327 --> 01:03:25.607
structure.
It says that the forward rate,

01:03:25.607 --> 01:03:29.206
which you can compute from
today's newspaper or from

01:03:29.206 --> 01:03:33.723
today's website--you can compute
the forward rates for all future

01:03:33.723 --> 01:03:36.356
dates.
What he says is those forward

01:03:36.356 --> 01:03:39.942
rates are what people think
interest rates will be in the

01:03:39.942 --> 01:03:43.719
future and that's called the
expectations theory of the term

01:03:43.719 --> 01:03:46.115
structure.
Forward rates equal expected

01:03:46.115 --> 01:03:49.044
future spot rates.
If you look at the December

01:03:49.044 --> 01:03:52.824
2003, what's going on?
It's very clear and that is the

01:03:52.824 --> 01:03:56.917
Fed had just cut interest rates
to 1%--it was unusual--it was

01:03:56.917 --> 01:04:00.535
much talked about.
People didn't expect that to

01:04:00.535 --> 01:04:04.750
hold and so people thought,
well it's going to still be

01:04:04.750 --> 01:04:07.559
down at 1% maybe in three
months.

01:04:07.559 --> 01:04:12.326
So, you can see the term
structure doesn't go up between

01:04:12.326 --> 01:04:16.288
overnight and three months.
But they are expecting that the

01:04:16.288 --> 01:04:18.859
Fed is eventually--and they were
right of course in this

01:04:18.859 --> 01:04:21.289
case--the Fed is eventually
going to raise rates.

01:04:21.289 --> 01:04:25.257
The upward-sloping term
structure means that the forward

01:04:25.257 --> 01:04:30.350
rates are at higher levels.
So, that's the expectations

01:04:30.350 --> 01:04:37.134
theory.
Hicks also talked about another

01:04:37.134 --> 01:04:45.690
theory in his 1939 book,
which is--there's the

01:04:45.690 --> 01:04:54.817
expectations theory,
but there's also a liquidity

01:04:54.817 --> 01:04:58.620
premium theory.

01:05:13.469 --> 01:05:20.620
This is the theory that there's
risk in longer-term bonds,

01:05:20.620 --> 01:05:27.394
so there's a tendency for
upward-sloping term structure

01:05:27.394 --> 01:05:31.660
even if expectations are flat.

01:05:34.679 --> 01:05:41.318
So, according to the
expectations theory augmented

01:05:41.318 --> 01:05:49.312
with liquidity preference--This
strongly upward-sloping term

01:05:49.312 --> 01:05:55.679
structure in 2003 would reflect
two things.

01:05:55.679 --> 01:05:59.831
One is that people expected
interest rates to go up and,

01:05:59.831 --> 01:06:03.303
secondly, that interest
rates–longer-term

01:06:03.303 --> 01:06:07.687
bonds--are riskier,
so there's also another effect

01:06:07.687 --> 01:06:12.298
pushing interest rates up.
The last thing I want to talk

01:06:12.298 --> 01:06:16.602
about is just--I'm running out
of time here and I want to

01:06:16.602 --> 01:06:19.829
mention this before your
mid-term exam,

01:06:19.829 --> 01:06:25.014
which is next Monday and covers
everything through this

01:06:25.014 --> 01:06:30.389
lecture--something about
inflation and interest rates.

01:06:30.389 --> 01:06:41.836
Inflation--we'll call that
π--the inflation rate is

01:06:41.836 --> 01:06:44.452
π.
So right now,

01:06:44.452 --> 01:06:47.881
it's something like 2% or it's
a little bit higher last year,

01:06:47.881 --> 01:06:50.110
but maybe it'll be 2% going
forward.

01:06:50.110 --> 01:06:57.952
The real interest rate,
computed from nominal rates,

01:06:57.952 --> 01:07:06.563
is equal to one plus the
nominal rate divided by one plus

01:07:06.563 --> 01:07:11.940
the inflation rate,
so it corrects for inflation.

01:07:11.940 --> 01:07:16.475
If you have an interest
rate--this is approximately

01:07:16.475 --> 01:07:21.555
equal to--one plus the real
interest rate is equal to one

01:07:21.555 --> 01:07:26.553
plus the nominal interest rate,
divided by one plus the rate of

01:07:26.553 --> 01:07:29.785
inflation.
So we would say the real

01:07:29.785 --> 01:07:36.572
interest rate equals the nominal
rate--approximately equals--the

01:07:36.572 --> 01:07:40.990
nominal rate minus the inflation
rate.

01:07:47.059 --> 01:07:50.297
If we have--right now,
if we go back to our current

01:07:50.297 --> 01:07:53.469
term structure–well,
this isn't complete.

01:07:53.469 --> 01:07:56.320
If you look at the current term
structure, it's interesting.

01:07:56.320 --> 01:07:59.429
Look how--this is as of earlier
this year;

01:07:59.429 --> 01:08:03.335
the Federal Funds Rate was at
around 4% and it has this huge

01:08:03.335 --> 01:08:06.512
drop in the term structure and
then it starts the

01:08:06.512 --> 01:08:08.750
upward-sloping.
Why is that?

01:08:08.750 --> 01:08:11.971
That's because on the date that
I got this term structure

01:08:11.971 --> 01:08:15.134
everybody knew the Fed was
cutting rates and they got it

01:08:15.134 --> 01:08:17.960
exactly right.
The Fed was cutting rates to 3%;

01:08:17.960 --> 01:08:20.760
they knew it was coming but not
today.

01:08:20.760 --> 01:08:26.980
Right now, we have a Federal
Funds Rate of about 3% and an

01:08:26.980 --> 01:08:33.310
inflation rate of around 3%,
so right now the real interest

01:08:33.310 --> 01:08:38.498
rate is close to 0.
Finally, I just want to say

01:08:38.498 --> 01:08:43.955
that we have also a kind of bond
called an indexed bond,

01:08:43.955 --> 01:08:49.710
which is a bond whose coupons
are indexed to inflation.

01:08:49.710 --> 01:08:54.614
With an indexed bond you don't
have to do this calculation to

01:08:54.614 --> 01:08:58.157
get the real rate.
The yield-to-maturity on an

01:08:58.157 --> 01:09:02.394
indexed bond is already in real
terms because the coupons are

01:09:02.394 --> 01:09:07.447
indexed to inflation.
In my final slide is a picture

01:09:07.447 --> 01:09:13.026
of the first indexed bond;
this is issued by the State of

01:09:13.026 --> 01:09:16.520
Massachusetts--I actually own
this bond.

01:09:16.520 --> 01:09:20.869
I bought it for $1,000 on a
website because I was interested

01:09:20.869 --> 01:09:24.122
in indexed bonds.
I could have brought it to

01:09:24.122 --> 01:09:28.183
class and showed it to you,
but this was issued during the

01:09:28.183 --> 01:09:31.390
Revolutionary War to help
finance the war.

01:09:31.390 --> 01:09:34.425
Now, what happened was the U.S.
Government--or the

01:09:34.425 --> 01:09:38.150
Massachusetts Government--had
created high inflation during

01:09:38.150 --> 01:09:41.938
the war and nobody wanted to
lend money to it so they create

01:09:41.938 --> 01:09:45.284
here a price index.
It says the price index

01:09:45.284 --> 01:09:49.677
contained this amount of beef,
this amount of sheep wool,

01:09:49.677 --> 01:09:54.069
this amount of sole leather,
and this amount of corn;

01:09:54.069 --> 01:09:58.075
that was the first consumer
price index ever used for

01:09:58.075 --> 01:10:01.127
financial contracts.
We now have something else

01:10:01.127 --> 01:10:05.649
called the Consumer Price Index.
This bond was paid off,

01:10:05.649 --> 01:10:11.856
the U.S.–Massa
chusetts--didn't fail to pay on

01:10:11.856 --> 01:10:18.046
it in 1784.
But anyway, indexed bonds are

01:10:18.046 --> 01:10:22.571
about 15% of the U.S.
national--I'm sorry,

01:10:22.571 --> 01:10:25.928
about 8% of the U.S.
national debt--about 15% of the

01:10:25.928 --> 01:10:28.290
U.K.
national debt--and they are

01:10:28.290 --> 01:10:32.310
very important but still a
minority of all of our fixed

01:10:32.310 --> 01:10:36.357
incomes.
That concludes this lecture and

01:10:36.357 --> 01:10:42.084
I won't be here on Monday,
but we'll have our lecture in

01:10:42.084 --> 01:10:43.817
this classroom on Monday.
 

